result.execSummary:
The defendant Terry E Young was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Felon Possess Firearm, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(2)(a).
  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Counts one and two.
Count three.

Defendant Terry E Young in court with attorney Walter Arthur Piel.  Defendant Terry E Young in custody.  Katherine Seelow appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 66 MONTHS with 101 days credit CONCURRENT to counts 2 and 3; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 30 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 36 MONTHS.

AS TO COUNT 2: The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 24 MONTHS with 101 days credit CONCURRENT to counts 1 and 3; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 12 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 12 MONTHS.

AS TO COUNT 3: The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Corrections with 101 days credit, CONCURRENT to counts 1 and 2. 

Court finds defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program but IS ELIGIBLE for the WI Substance Abuse program.

Conditions of Extended Supervision:
- No firearms, ammunition, body armor or no voting until rights have been restored.
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol.
- Random urine screens.
- Obtain/maintain full-time employment. 
-  Defendant is to complete 40 hours of community service.
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.
Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA); 
All applicable fees of supervision.
- Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and restitution be paid through collection from any court ordered obligations from the defendant's prison funds in an amount or percentage determined by DOC and as a condition of extended supervision. Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm. 
Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.
Court advised defendant that he/she may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.  

20 day appeal rights given,

Defendant Terry E Young in court with attorney Glen B. Kulkoski.  Katherine Seelow appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Opening statements made by the state and the defense. Court trial proceeded.  Sworn for the state: Milwaukee Police Officer Patrick Coe.  Exhibits 1-11 received.   Court breaks for lunch.  Court trial continues.  Stipulations (2) received and filed.  Court took judicial notice of stipulations.  Court finds upon questioning, the defendant knowingly, intelligently and voluntarily agreed to the stipulations.  Sworn for the state: Milwaukee Police Forensic Investigator Lee Vedbraaten.  Exhibit 12 received.  Sworn for the state: WI State Crime Laboratory DNA Analyst Emily Schmitt.  Exhibit 13 received.  State rests subject to rebuttal.  Court finds upon questioning, the defendant knowingly, intelligently and voluntarily agreed to testify.  Sworn for defense: Terry Young.  Defense rests.  Sworn for state as rebuttal witness: Milwaukee Police Officer Patrick Coe.  Exhibit 14 received and published.  State and defense rest.  For reasons stated on the record, Court finds the defendant GUILTY of Count 1.  Court granted state's motion for judgment on the verdict and denied defense motion for judgment not withstanding the verdict.  Court ordered entry of judgment of conviction.  Exhibit list received and filed.  Case adjourned for sentencing in Branch 22.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for November 2, 2016 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Terry E Young in court with attorney Glen B. Kulkoski.  Katherine Seelow appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  As to Counts 2 & 3: Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.

As to Count 1-  Court finds upon questioning, the defendant knowingly, intelligently and voluntarily waived right to jury trial.  Defense wishes to proceed with a court trial as to Count 1.  Waiver of trial by jury received and filed.  Court trial scheduled for August 29, 2016 at 10:00 am.
